segments.text: and how you came to be, maybe.
My full name is Eugene Thomas Skidmore.
And very few people in this state know that.
And most all of the veterinarians know me as Zeke.
It's a nickname I came by when I was in high school, and it went all the way through college, and it's still with me.
The only people that call me Eugene are people that do not know me.
They call me on the phone trying to sell me something.
And you're immediately on alert.
Or my immediately family, and they call me Gene.
That is family on my side of the family.
The rest of them don't, but I was born in the Depression, and my father died about four months before I was born, so I was raised by a widow woman.
And we moved to Texas in 1940.
So you were not born in Texas?
No, I was born in Des Moines, Iowa.
Oh, okay.
And we moved to Texas in 1943.
And had my 11th birthday the day after we arrived.
I went to finish elementary school and high school in El Paso, Texas.
Graduated from El Paso High School in 1950 and entered Texas A&M the same year.
How did you get to Texas A&M?
On the train.
No, I mean, I had a long train ride, too, wasn't it?
Yeah, it was.
The reason I went to Texas A&M is that along in the middle of my high school career, I knew that I wanted to work with horses.

Being a family of very, very modest means, there's no way that I was ever going to be able to work on horses of my own, and I thought it would be a very good way to make a living, be working on somebody else's animals, and the best way I could think of was to go to vet school.
Did you have a horse?
No, I had plenty to ride.

I was fortunate that there was quite a few people in the area that had lots of money and they had horses and they didn't have time to ride them and they paid me to ride them and I trained their horses to where I could rope off of and so I had plenty of horses to rope from.
In those days nobody had trailers, at least us kids didn't have trailers and we would
get up Sunday morning and go to a rope and it'd be twenty miles away and ride a horse and lead three.
And we got there, we'd have a fresh horse to rope on and have something to come back on.
And you were a cowboy.
No, I was a roper.
Okay, okay.
But I investigated and found the only place that I could go to vet school in the state was in Texas A&M.
I said, well, here I come.
So you really knew what you were going to do?
I knew what I wanted to do.
I enrolled at A&M, and they issued me a uniform, and some guy ran up to me and says, hey, you got to call all these guys sir and all that.
I said, that's a bunch of bull.
I didn't know anything about Texas A&M.

I didn't know anything about Texas A&M, and I was in for a shock, and I became gung-ho like most everybody else does in Aggie in the Corps, and I went along with it, and I think it's one of the best things that ever happened.
I hate to see the Corps go downhill,
But with that many students, it's got two, and it's coed now.
But I interviewed to get into vet school after I finished my two years of pre-vet, or during my two years of pre-vet.
And I had an interview with the dean once before that.
And my sophomore year in pre-vet, I made an F in chemistry at midterm.
On my second major quiz, I froze.
And it's about five minutes before the end of the class before I even got my name spelled right.
And I heard through the test, missing all kinds of subscripts and everything.
I made 50 on it, and I ended up with a- That's pretty good.
Oh, I thought so.
That was pretty good, considering- I thought so.
And anyway, I ended up with the-
69 average in the course.
And at that time, 70 was passing.
And everybody that was failing the course had to go see the dean.
And the dean at that time of the veterinary college was Dr. Boughton.
And all the rumors about him, that was a mean man.
And he had just gotten out of the hospital.
He'd had a stroke.
And he had a cane that he walked with.
And he swung that cane.
And he cussed.
And he banged the desk and all of that.
So I arrived at his office when I was assigned to, and he sent me down in there, and he says, boy, what's the matter with you?
I started saying, shut up.
He says, your grades are awful.
I said, but sir, he says, what about this trig grade?
I had a 100 average in trig, and I said, sir, shut up.
He says, what about your physics grade?
I said, sir, I had a
Ninety-nine something, and he asked me, shut up!
What about this chemistry?
I think I'd, shut up!
And he read all these things, and he kept telling me to shut up.
And he finally says, okay, now, he says, you just wanted to talk, says, what, what do you got to say for yourself?
I says, sir?
I thought 100 average was about as good as you could do in trig.
And 99-something in physics was not so bad.
And I went down to him, and I got the chemistry.
And I said, I got a 69 in chemistry.
And I says, I think I can bring that up to a B.
And he looked at me, and he says, what's your name?
And I told him, he says, oh, God.
And he pulled me across there, and he said.
He had the wrong guy.
The guy hadn't even passed P.E.
Oh, my gosh.
And I don't know who that guy was.
But he was going to catch it.
But anyway, as crippled as Dr. Boughton was, he got up, he shook my hand, and he walked with me to the door and with his big buddies.
Everything was fine.
He said, you think you can make a B in that camera?
I said, I'm pretty sure that I can.
And the next close encounter I had with Dr. Boughton was on the interview.
Now, I've talked to quite a few people, and my daughter being one of them, that the difference is the way they interview them nowadays and when they did it in those days.

Nowadays they have a committee of three that interview people and they make an appointment sometime during the day and they talk with them for an hour or so and they score them and it's all written down as to how many points you get.
If you're going to get the total number of points
all three of them have to agree that you need a total.
If you're going to get a zero, all three of them have to agree that it's a zero, and if it's a split decision, you get it in the middle, and that's the way your interaction goes.

But in the days that we went, they had most of the interviews at night after class, but they didn't want you to miss any class, and it was after dark when I went in there, and you went in the dean's office, and they had this swivel chair in the middle of the room.
And the department heads were in chairs all the way around the room.
Oh boy, that's the hot box.
And they'd ask you all kinds of questions, not necessarily pertaining to your studies, because they had your transcript, they knew what your grades were.
And never, while I was in there, was a question asked by a person who I was facing.
It was always from behind.
And you turn around and face the person and you ask them a question and you just about finish your answer.
And the guy behind you asks you one.
You spin around and you answer him.
And you just about got dizzy and then all of a sudden knocked about and says, okay, interview's over.
And you take out and bring somebody else in.
And you had no idea of what kind of impression you made.
Because you couldn't see the faces of the people.
You were too scared to even recognize what they were.
Inquisition almost, doesn't it?
Inquisition, it was.
And in those days, being that Dr. Baffin was the dean, you had to swear to be damned that when you graduate, you're going to West Texas and work on sheep and goats.
And that was the thing.
That got you.
That was going to get you in.
That got you.
But anyway, I got in.
And it was a enjoyable time.
When I first got in, all of the veterinary college was on the main campus.
And after the second year, they moved the hospital over across the tracks.
And the time that I was a senior, they had moved the basic science on over there.
They had finished the building there, and they had all of the vet school there on the other side of the track scene.
It is only a very small part of the buildings that are there right now.
Yeah.
It is a very small part.
But we thought it was great.
We were really in the high top cotton.
It was really something.
Yeah.
So you started, let me get the chronology right, you went to A&M.
1950 is when I started as a freshman in pre-med, and September of 1952 is when I got into medical school, and I graduated in May 1956.
We started out with 64 in our class, and we graduated 54.
As a contrast to the way it is today, they run about twice as many students now.
They run somewhere between about 128.
And at that time, we had a faculty total of 19 people.
They have more than that in the anatomy department now.
And that was counting the dean.
Yeah.
That was different.
And they were handling relatively large loads.
Well, half the number of students where they are now.
Of course, the technology wasn't near as much.
No, that's it.
That world has really changed.
We had three clinicians in the small animal.
We had three clinicians in the large animal.
We had two people in anatomy.
We had one in parasitology and about three in... You remember any special people there you remember?
Dr. Turk, everybody remembers.
You know, everybody does.
Dr. Turk is one of the biggest philosophers
that veterinary medicine has ever had.
I mean, he always had a good outlook, always, everything was funny.
He enjoyed life.
His death, he wore hearing aid and therefore he talked kind of funny.
He did.
And he was always pulling the gag on somebody, but one of the smartest
minds that she ever was.
He had a master's in parasitology and he confers PhDs on people.
He was that good.
He was one of the most highly recognized parasitologists in the country.
But he had no need or reason to go and get a PhD.
He knew all the stuff.
He was training PhDs.
And a likable man you never saw any more likable.
He and I got into a real good thing and he
was one that always said that he didn't want anybody bringing him a paper complaining about a grade unless it's going to make a difference in their total grade.
I mean, he didn't want to worry about it.
There's going to be a few mistakes.
Well, he made a big error on that.
Well, he took off one point on it and there's a place on the back where he should have taken off ten more.
He had it marked, but he didn't subtract.
He just batted the subtraction.
And so I went up there and showed him, and man, he jumped on me with both feet for bothering him with that thing.
Because I was complaining about a 98.
And I said, but sir, but sir, man, he's really cussing me.
But I flipped over and said, but what about this ten you're supposed to take off?
I never had anybody come back.
He says, if anyone says, I'll split the difference with you, they'll still give you an A.
And I got an A in the course.
I've had that happen a couple times, once or twice since I've been teaching.
And that's about what I did.
I said, OK, I'll give you an A.
All of a sudden, I was doing better in the course, too.
I was learning more.
I got out of it.
I got more assistance from him.
Oh, you appreciate that.
You remember a guy who does that.
Well, the year I graduated, I
I was waiting to go in the Army, and when you've got an Army hanging over you, nobody wants to hire you.
And so I went to work with the government.
They can't do anything there.
They've got to take you even if you're going to go to the Army.
So I'd been working with the Army, and the ABMA convention was in San Antonio.
And the government sent all of us in Texas down there to the convention, and I'd seen Turk.
And I was going to lunch with them, and I was going down the street, and I heard this holler.
I guess somebody hollered, hey, Zeke!
And I looked up, and Turk was sitting on the fender of a car about a half a block away.
Come here!
Get on down here!
So I turned around and come back.
He says, the fella here wants you to meet.
He says, you work for the government.
He says, you need to know this guy.
He says, Van Halen, he's the head man, you know, from Washington.
No kidding.
He says, you need to know this guy.
He says, he's your boss.
He says, he's your boss.
He says, you're getting on a good side of him.
Your next boss, he's going to have to answer to him.
He says, get to know this guy.
Get to know this guy.
He's just a regular down-to-earth sort of person.
And he was interesting to his students.
Oh, Lord.
I mean, all of his students liked him.
He was great.
And they say everything was nice and funny.
He was a serious man.
He took everything serious, but
Not so seriously.
There wasn't humor in things.
He was very, very humorous.
Like the story he told on himself that Dr. Batten called him up and wondered, says, what was it you told this Miss so-and-so?
Says, who?
Miss so-and-so.
She called me and said that the guy with that hearing aid over there was a smart aleck.
Oh, her.
Says, well, what did you tell her?
Says, she came over there and she was worried.
Says,
She wanted me to do something, said her cat was up in the tree and couldn't get down.
I said, well, what did you tell her?
She said, I just told her not to worry about it.
I said, I've never seen no cat skeletons in a tree.
But this is just the way he approached things.
When you got out of school, when you graduated, you went to service.
Well, first I went to work for the government.
I tested cows for the government, and...
They could have kept me out of the service.
All I had to do was sign my name and I would have got a deferment.
And I told them, I said, well, I may want to spend my life working for the government, but I want to do it on my terms.
I don't want you to say, okay, now, if you want to quit, well, hey, then you're going to have to go to the army now.
I said, I'm going to get my army out of the way.
And if I come back, anytime I want to.
Another thing that Dr. Turk always told us, he says,
Always have you a license.
Keep your license paid up.
He said, you may have a job that doesn't require a license.
He says, but they come give you a hard time.
He said, you just point at your license and say, hey, man, I can go work for myself.
He says, if you don't have one of those, you're out of their funds.
And so I remember that.
And I told him, I said, well, I'm going to go to service.
So I had it made all the time that I was in the service.
I hate to even mention how easy that I did have it.
I had checked with them and I had sent in application for commission and they sent it back.
It was Charlie Wilson who cut them out and said there might be a few around but there's going to wait for those that have been called rather than just take them in.
Says keep the application and when you get your call, send it back and tell us that you've gotten your draft notice.
It hadn't been all ready to go.
And I went back and talked to the draft board to see what it was all about.
And they said, OK, when you send that in, did you send us a letter requesting us to hold up your thing?
I said, but we can't hold it up until we get word from them that they're processing the commission.
I said, fine.
Well, I got my paperwork, and I dropped the envelope in the mail right then.
I sent the other envelope that I already had made out to the draft board saying, hold up.
Well, by return mail, I got my commission application back and a letter and said that I'd have gotten my draft notice and said that they didn't have any commissions available.
Sorry.
And so I said, well, I've got to go.
So I quit my job with the government and went home and showed up to the draft board.
And they put me on a bus in downtown El Paso, carried me out to Fort Bliss.

heard everybody in the room, and this sergeant ran up to the front and says, okay, everybody stay there in your chair until I call your name, then come up here, grab this bottle of pee in it, and sit it over there and wait in line.
He called out all these names he got through, and he was pulling up his thing, and I was sitting down there, and he looked down and he says, what are you doing sitting down there?
He told me to sit here, and he called my name.
I hadn't heard it yet.
Come up here.
I said, what's your name?
And I told him, and he couldn't find it.
I said, let me see your draft card.
So I showed it to him, and well,
After I'd gotten my degree, well, the draft board stamped across my card, special registration, because it also registered for the doctor's draft.
He read letters across the front that said special registration.
He said, sit down, sir.
Sit down.
Just a minute.
He took off.
He came back with the major.
The major wanted to see my draft card.
Sit down, sir.
Sit down, sir.
Boy, I mean, I was really somebody.
He took me to the major's office, and they called the draft board.
And the draft board didn't want to talk to him, says, let me talk to Dr. Skidmore.
got on the phone with the girl's grandpa and says, hey, we got your letter.
He says, we're holding up your paper.
He says, you don't have to go if you don't want to.
I said, well, you told me.
He says, ah, don't worry about it.
He says, if you don't want to go, why don't you go?
Just tell them adios.
Yeah, that's a hard moment of decision.
There you are sitting there.
Now, I had already talked to the base veterinarian there, and he says, now, they're doing basic training here.
He says, I'll try to get you, as soon as basic training's over, get you into the veterinary service, and then we'll work on getting you a commission.
Well, I didn't stay there for basic training.
They sent me off to Fort Hood.
And I went through...
basic training there and being an A&M graduate and had a good bit of the military, and they were short-handed.
They had very little cadre.
They had three officers and four sergeants to take care of a whole company of men and train them.
So I taught 50% of the class.
I was made an Aggie sergeant.
I was the only guy in the company that could go to the PX and drink beer anytime I wanted to.
But I had it made.
And then for the next bit, I went to Stele at Fort Hood.
Because I wanted to stay at Fort Hood because I could go back and forth to Palestine and see my wife.
I wasn't married to yet.
And then the whole bunch was being sent to Germany as replacements in the 3rd Army Division.
So I got married three weeks before I shipped out to Germany.
And she stayed here and I shipped out to Germany and we got on the ship and it had
When we was down in the hole, the peons down there in the hole, it was awful.
Anyway, the word got out that I was a veterinarian, so they called me up, and there was dependents that had pets.
And says, hey, will you take care of the pet deck?
And it was a deck that was a little bit bigger than these two rooms together, and they had a fancy cage.
They said, you don't have to do anything.
They've got to feed them, and they've got to walk around.
But you keep the deck clean.
And nobody's allowed up here besides the dependents.
And I looked down and, golly, GI's everywhere.
You don't have a place to stand, sit, or anything.
I had this all to myself.
I said, I'll take it.
I'll take it.
Well, anyway, one of the guys that were there with the pet happened to be the first sergeant that was going over.
And he was in charge of the veterinary division at Market Center.
I got to talking to him.
He says, well, that's a bad deal.
He says, as soon as I get there, I'll talk to Colonel Watson.
He says, we'll get you changed over to the veterinary services.
We got enlisted people and the like.
I mean, I didn't even know a lot about the veterinary services.
He says, we'll get you there.
First chance you get, you come in to Frankfort, and we'll see about getting you changed.
And I told him where I was going to go and everything.
Well, I no sooner got to where I was supposed to be
And they moved me to another plant.
And so they couldn't find me.
And I was trying my best to get in Frankfurt.
I stationed in Hanau, about 50 kilometers out of Frankfurt.
You know, work all day, and the market center closed on the weekends, and this, that, and the other.
Well, the first sergeant that comes through the barracks one day says, next Thursday is the 4th of July.
He says, it's a holiday.
He says, but I'm taking volunteers for a parade.
He says, we've got to have a parade on the 4th of July, and anybody that volunteers for a parade will have the 5th off.
I said, take me.
Take me.
That's what you've been looking for.
Get out.
Shoot, I was on the drill team and everything.
In college, I wasn't afraid to go for a parade.
Most of those guys didn't know how to march, let alone go for a parade.
It's awful.
Anyway, I went.
right and early the next minute I went on a train to Frankfurt.
I went up there and told them where I was, what I was doing, and everything.
And they said, well, we'll check on you.
We'll work you.
And all of the time that I talked to them in the meantime, I told them, you know, I'd like to get out.
And it's impossible, it is absolutely impossible to transfer out of the Third Army.
And I told them that.
I said, well, I said,
You just be quiet.
He says, we'll take care of things.
Well, the next Monday, when I got back from work at noon, the guys in the barracks that work personnel says, hey, somebody down in Frankfort knows you.
I said, yeah.
He says, the major's been on the phone all morning about you.
I said, what's going on?
We had dinner, and I was sitting around the barracks waiting to go back to work, and the major comes up.
All of a sudden, he's a buddy-buddy, and he says, say, who do you know down in Frankfort?
I said, I don't know who's down there.
And he looked at me and said, well, some of the, I don't know.
And he, and all this went on for a couple weeks.
He was calling this, that, and the other.
And my spies in there kept telling me, he says, you know, they're working on it.
And Major's trying to give so-and-so, I mean, he's a guy with about 45 IQ, he's trying to send them over there, and this, that, and the other.
And so I did get back into Frankfort to see him once again, and they said, well, we,
About got this deal worked.
Says, you play ignorant.
Says, but next week, says, you're going to get orders to be transferred to us.
And your orders are going to say that you're supposed to go to Holland.
Says, but that's not a good post.
We're going to change you to Copenhagen.
Says, you, when you get them,
you tell them to just send you to Market Center and we'll take care of everything."
He says, "'Cause you can't go to Holland anyway or Copenhagen, either one, because all you got is a uniform and you can't go in there with a uniform.
You gotta go in civilian clothes."
So the Major and the First Sergeant, they kept asking me a few questions.
I didn't know anything.
Colonel Watson had told me, he said, you know, the less you know, the better off anyway.
And so they had
I was a very sorry radio operator, so they sent me to typing school because it's good to give you teletypewriters and teach me to type so I can run a teletypewriter.
And one afternoon, the first sergeant called over and says, turn in your typewriter.
He says, you're going to Holland.
He says, get your foot over here to the, he says, I've got two days to get you out of here.
So I went over there and I said, now, sergeant, I said, all you got to do is clear me post, get through the
Captain's driver took me and dumped me down at the Market Center in Frankfort.
He said, I can't do that.
Your orders ain't safe.
I said, look, how come just two hours ago you're saying that now you know what's the matter?
But anyway, I convinced him to call, and I had the number, and I told him to call Colonel Watson and get the scoop on it.
The colonel says, just send him down here, and we'll take care of him.
He says, I'll be your back.
Anyway, I got down there, and they
I stayed a couple of days while they processed me and changed my orders and issued me civilian clothes and sent me to Copenhagen where I was assigned to the embassy.
Well, that's nice.
That's where our office was.
But we was inspecting meat and foods, all dairy products and everything that was produced in Denmark.
It was going to the troops in Germany.
But Denmark did not allow uniformed foreign troops on their soil.
So we all wore civilian clothes.
And it was a nice place.
It's a clean place.
At the time, I smoked.
And I wouldn't dare drop a cigarette butt on the street, because I'd be the only one in town.
I'd go back to the embassy, and both of my suit pockets would be full of cigarette butts.
And I'd empty them out in a wastebasket.
It's a clean town.
If you dropped your gum on the street, you wouldn't be afraid to pick it up and put it back in your mouth.
It is very nice.
The people are nice, friendly, and all.
Anyway, while I was there, I got a letter from my brother.
He sent me a card that said the 4th Army, which is in Texas, had an opening for a veterinarian they wanted me to send in my application.
So I told the colonel, I said, hey, they got one here for that thing that's for 4th Army.
Just a minute, he got on the phone and they got him to change that allocation for 7th Army, which is here.
And so I had to go take a physical and all that kind of stuff.
And they sent me down to Frankfort to get a physical.
I had no sooner flown back, and the colonel says, you got to go back to Frankfort.
that they didn't get a full picture of your chest on x-rays.
I said, I'm six foot two, and I've got 30 inch legs.
I'm all chest.
And they missed it.
They missed it.
They just missed it.
They missed part of it.
So I had to fly back to Frankfurt.
They took another picture of my chest, and they processed the, I think it took them about four weeks to process the commission for me.
And in the States, it takes about 12 or so weeks.
Yeah, you were living sort of a charmed life.
I was.
That's what I say.
I mean, I had it.
Why didn't I stay in the Army?
Yeah.
I wanted to be a veterinary practitioner.
I didn't want to be there to begin with.
But it was all the way through, it was a nice thing for me.
In fact, I signed the papers.
My executive officer signed the papers.
The commander signed the papers.
The special courier took them to Frankfurt.
They signed the papers and they went by special courier to Heidelberg, which is the USAR headquarters in the
the chief user of veterinarian signed them there and they hand carried them and woke up a two-star general in the middle of the night to get the authorization for it.
And he had already said, now whatever time they come in, get me up and I'll sign them.
And at two o'clock in the morning they woke him up and he signed the papers and got a teletype to Washington to get the thing.
I mean, it's all working for them.
Yeah, it really is.
The bad part of it was then they thought maybe I'd want to stay in the service.
And there I was in a place that didn't even wear uniforms anymore.
So they transferred me to Munich, which is a very nice place, if you've never been to Copenhagen.
If you've never been to Copenhagen, it's a real nice place, but it's a step down.
Tough life you're living.
Tough life.
But they had an officer there that was a regular Army officer in a very
and they wanted to be sure that I knew how to operate as a military officer if I ever did want to stay.

And what really chapped me is as a PFC in Denmark, being that there's no military and no PX and this and that, with all of the different pay and all that I got, I jumped from PFC to a first lieutenant and moved to Munich and as a first lieutenant
In the veterinary corps, I got an extra $100 a month professional pay, and it cost me about $100 a month to do that.
I mean, I was making more as a PSC than I was as a...
But anyway, I had to sign up for two years from that time, and my wife had already come over.
I made her way over, and we lived there in Munich for two years, and our oldest child was born there about
five weeks before we came back.
Just old, just was old enough to travel.
And I went ahead and got out and went to work in a private practice in Gainesville.
In Gainesville?
Gainesville, Texas, up on the Red River.
How'd you get there?
I had put an ad in the ABMA Journal that I was, would be available in January of 1950.
And I got this letter that this was available, and it was on my way, because I drove from New York down, and so I just stopped by there and checked with them.
On the way to Palestine, where my wife and daughter were, they flew back.
Incidentally, they had... Go ahead.
Was this a practice that you were buying?
No, no, I was just going to work for him.
You were open up.
I was just going to go work for this guy.
Oh, okay.
He had a practice doctor, Gordon Yergin.
Okay.
And he said, yeah, come to work as soon as you can.
So I went and spent Christmas with my in-laws and went back up there and found a place to live.
And it was just for a two-year period because his associate had gone to the service.
And so I was there for two years.
And I feel that any...
veterinarian, you're not required to intern as a veterinarian.
But all veterinarians, when they graduate, should work with another practitioner.
Because there's a lot of things that you can learn they do not, cannot, should not teach you in school.
Well, that's the way with Alec Sears.
Apparently, he opened up his office flat, cold,
He's Texas, wherever it was.
Anyway, he had, and I kind of followed this because not many people do that, and that's ill-advised, but he had a really strong background in economics.
And I have a sense that that was a big plus for him.
Apparently he set up a practice, and it was a marketable thing.
He sold it in two years and then moved over here.
Yeah.
See, it's very difficult to practice economics.
like you should.
And be a businessman too.
And well not only that, but see they teach you the exact procedure like it should be done in school, which they should.
But then there are a lot of shortcuts that you need to do if you're going to make a living at it.
And you need to learn.
And one of the big examples is the first day I went into this practice, I had to remove a cancer eye from a cow.
And I did just like the book and how they taught me in school.
And it took me about four hours to do it, and it was a sorry job.
The day I left, I had to take a cat's ride out of Macau.
From the time the guy drove up to the time he drove off was 20 minutes, and it was a darn good job.
I mean, it's experience and a few things that you learn to do, and it may not be the exact procedure, but it is better.
Because when you're in school, you don't care about time.
You're learning.
It's a learning process.
The more sutures you make, the better you get at suturing.
When you're making a liver, the fewer sutures you make, the quicker you get done.
And it's that simple.
It changes your whole...
Anyway, I went to... That's a good point.
There for two years, and then I tried to put in a practice in my old hometown in El Paso, and I could not get any zoning like I needed.
Okay, I picked up on that a lot too.
I went to the zoning board and where I really had trouble with the zoning board, I think there were seven people on the zoning board.
And to get a variance, you had to have six of them for you.
There was one guy on the zoning board that he vowed, and it was made public, that he would not ever vote
for a variance.
Because if there should be a variance, it should change the law.
And the variances were not.
He would not vote for a variance.
So it would take a unanimous of the others to get it.
One of the others was a wife of a veterinarian in town.
So she would abstain because of it.
So there's no way I can get six votes.
And so I worked as a day laborer at a new post office there.
I worked as a day laborer.
Is that right?
Yeah, just to keep going while I was trying to get this zoning.
And it was at Christmas time so I worked nights at the post office sorting mail.
And I soon quit that night job because I had to get home one time while my daughter was awake and she was hiding behind her mother like she didn't even recognize me.
I said, this isn't going to get it.
So in the meantime, I needed somebody back in his practice, an additional body.
So I went back there with him for about six months.
And a classmate of mine was going to go to Guam and was wanting to lease out his practice in Mesquite.
So I leased his practice and went there.
And this is one of the big reasons that I went there.
When you go to work for somebody, you always have this wonder if people are using you just because they can't get to the guy you're working for.
I mean, you're just a second choice.
And you wonder if you can do it on your own.
So you want to have this idea.
I am going to be the man.
And anything that I get is because they came to see me, not because they couldn't get the other guy.
So you've got to have this.
It's there.
And it's what I tell so many guys that hire people to work for them.
And they say, golly, I hired him.
I said, boy, he's real good.
And I thought he'd stay with me.
But he left.
I said, he had never been on his own.
I said, if you want somebody to stay, hire somebody that's already been on his own once.
Then he'll stay.
Gee, never thought of that.
But anyway, it's a built-in thing.
So I went there and found out that I could do it myself and felt good about it.
Then he came back and we were going to be partners and we didn't get along too good.
Everybody has differences in any way.
Dan Anderson then was needing somebody, so I came over here to work.
I went to work with Dan Anderson.
I worked with him for about 11 years, and I decided to go on my own tour in Euless, and moved to Euless, and I've been there ever since.
Now, when you first came to, well, Gainesville, let's say, with Dan Anderson, are you in large animal?
Are you horses?
Horses, cattle, general practices are those things.
You don't turn anything.
Anything, okay.
I said chickens and snakes.
That's about the only thing I turned down is chickens and snakes.
In hope that nobody brought me hogs, but I did work them.
But did you get in the same way?
I guess you did.
At what point did you notice that your practice was distinctly changing, when you were with Dan Anderson or when you were on your own at Euless?
When I was on my own at Euless, when I was with Dan, that's when we were doing the work for Bone and Hunt, both of us.
I was doing most of it out there.
And I told you about how they kind of gave me a glancing eye, but once it was established
I mean, I don't want to sound like I'm a blowhard, but I was a good veterinarian, and that's what it is.
Good psychology, that's right.
I just wanted to sell my veterinary skills, not my ability to round up cattle and all that kind of stuff.
And that's when I was working for Dan Anderson, and we did a good bit of charlay people in the work out around.
Once you go to working for some of them that are in a group,

And particularly if you're capable of handling their sails for them, get their animals ready for sale, get them tested and their ghouls fertility tested and all that, and being able to handle them, all of a sudden they flock in on you and we'd have a sale going on most all the time, and it was nice.
And these people paid money.
They never did ask about, oh, gee, you're charging us too much, or this, that, and the other.
We sent them a bill, and if I returned mail, you'd get it back.
Well, I didn't say return mail.
Here's another thing that I've learned.
A lot of these big people, and you don't need to mention this until you've done your hunts, number one, these big corporations, they'll float no matter who it is.
If there's not a thing, they'll put off paying you for years and years and years if they can.
It's a way of doing business.
Well, when I was in Gainesville,
I happened to learn from a fellow station that took care of my car.
He's a mechanic and he's having trouble getting money out of these old field trucks he's working on.
Slumber J and you know, these big things.
He's working, he sent him a bill and you know, he'd eventually get it and he wasn't getting it.
And one of the drivers then told him, he says, what you've got to do, and I remember this and this is what we did the whole time.
He says, what you've got to do when you do work for them, he says,
charge them about 25% more than you do other people, send them their bill, and tell them if they pay you within 10 days to take a 10% discount.
And you're still ahead.
And you're still ahead.
And in 10 days, you get your money just like that.
That's good technology.
So some of our big ones that were a little bit slow, we'd do that.
We'd charge them a little bit more and put on their bill.
We'd pay in 10 days, deduct so much, and we'd give them a pretty good discount.
Just like that, you get a return.
And that's true for any kind of business.
Because I gather that's another problem in veterinary medicine.
It's collecting.
In a small animal, in my business now, I have no accounts receivable.
My charges are MasterCard and Visa.
And I just tell them that my banker told me that if I didn't loan money, he wouldn't treat animals.
And we've got a deal going.
That's good, yeah.
And this is the way it works.
It's old.
It gets stung every now and then.
A lot of times they don't have their money with them.
There's a lot of things that never wait to decay.
And we do it.
Now, it gets stung every now and then, but unfortunately not too often.
Any of it, it hurts.
So now, but when did you begin to know?
Let's talk about the large animal, small animal conversion.
I noticed.
Because when I moved to Euless, I had a large animal hospital.
I bought it from a person who was only using it for small animals at the time.
But it had large animal facilities there.
We had a nice small animal clinic.
We had a large animal surgery, large animal treatment room, a barn with four stalls.
We had all of the facilities for large and small animals.
And what year is this?
Do you remember?
So I did make a practice and I had a band and I made calls and this and that.
And like I say, north of me there was wide open country, lots of horses and all.
And then they started building.
And then in 1984, it was just about crowding me out.
I mean, I'd have to travel too far to do horses, except race horses.
And I could not find a race horse trainer that would use me.
Because I would only treat them with what medications I thought they ought to have, not the medications that they wanted me to give them.
And that just didn't work out.
So most of my horse work was individual owners.
And they'd just been moved out.
So I didn't have that much work.
And way out for cattle, and that's by myself if I spent
several hours gone just going and coming while I had to charge them so much that they couldn't afford me and be gone from a small animal practice that I couldn't do anything.
And then the local bank came and said, we're doing real good and we're going to put in another bank and this location is a place that we'd like to have in the area around here.
So I got to looking and to fix that place up like I wanted would cost me a bundle.
And so they cut me a deal that I could get out from under what I owed some.
I sold them the place and I put in there a small animal practice in a shopping center.
And I moved from about a 6,000 square foot hospital to a 1,200 square foot hospital.
Do you have a partner's now?
Well, I moved into that place in 84.
And my daughter graduated from vet school in 85 and was taking her to come there.
So she graduated, I put her name on the window.
She came in and she worked with me until October, because in the meantime there's a practice that became available and we was able to, well it was before she graduated and I was trying to negotiate.
Even then, you know, funds are hard to get by, this, that, and the other, and it took until October that we were able to swing the deal and we got it for her over there.
So she's out there, but we function for each other.
I mean, if I've got to be gone a half day or anything, well, we'll schedule it.
She'll come to my place and do it, and I'll go to hers and help her.
Or maybe she's got something she needs some help on, well, I'll go there during the day or at noontime or whatever.

And being that she's a lot younger and had a much more technical education than I have, there's a lot of things I'll call her, hey, how about this, that, and the other, and she'll call me and say, hey, Dad, didn't they used to use such and such?
We complement each other.
And it works real nice, and I enjoy it.
She's independent, you're independent.
That's right, yeah.

Well, that was originally.

and he was quite active in that.
